The instruction asks how to sum values in column B for rows whose dates in column A match a given month listed in the result area. Since the month names are plain text (`July`, `August`) rather than full dates, a practical LibreOffice-compatible formula is to compare the month text produced from the date using `TEXT(date,"MMMM")` and sum with `SUMPRODUCT`.

To address the “ignore zero instead of getting zero in the sum” part, the cleanest literal implementation in this sheet is to sum only matching rows; if no matches or only zero amounts existed, `SUMPRODUCT` naturally contributes nothing from those rows. For this workbook, writing the month-based aggregation formula into `B10:B11` is the relevant spreadsheet manipulation.

